# BugME — AI Study Buddy

BugME is a full-stack study companion for students. Upload course PDFs, get AI-generated study guides and quizzes, and sync an exam-prep schedule to Google Calendar with email and popup reminders.

## Features

- **PDF upload** — Parse lecture notes and syllabi (OCR when needed) via the Flask backend.
- **AI study guide** — Gemini builds a structured guide from your notes.
- **Quiz generation** — Auto-generated quizzes to test understanding.
- **AI teach mode** — Interactive explanations from uploaded material.
- **AI study schedule** — Topic-by-topic deadlines before midterms and finals, based on your guide and quizzes.
- **Google Calendar sync** — One-click sync of the AI schedule to your primary calendar, with configurable reminders (popup + email).
- **Course dashboard** — Per-course hub for guides, quizzes, calendar, and uploads.
- **Firebase auth** — Google sign-in with per-user data stored in Firestore.

## Tech stack

| Layer | Tools |
|-------|--------|
| Frontend | React 19, Vite, Tailwind CSS, React Router |
| Backend | Python 3.12, Flask, PyMuPDF, pytesseract |
| AI | Google Gemini (`google-genai`) |
| Auth & data | Firebase Auth, Firestore, Firebase Admin SDK |

## Prerequisites

- **Node.js** 18+ (LTS recommended)
- **Python** 3.12
- **Tesseract OCR** (for scanned PDFs): `brew install tesseract` on macOS
- Firebase project with Google sign-in enabled
- Google Cloud project with **Gemini API** and **Google Calendar API** enabled

## Local setup

### 1. Clone and install

```bash
git clone https://github.com/keshavgarg616/BugME.git
cd BugME
```

**Backend**

```bash
cd backend
python3.12 -m venv ../venv
source ../venv/bin/activate   # Windows: ..\venv\Scripts\activate
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Place your Firebase service account JSON at `backend/firebase-admin-key.json` (not committed; see `.gitignore`).

**Frontend**

```bash
cd frontend
npm install
```

### 2. Environment variables

**Frontend** — create `frontend/.env`:

```env
VITE_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your-api-key
VITE_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
VITE_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
VITE_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
VITE_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=your-sender-id
VITE_FIREBASE_APP_ID=your-app-id
```

**Backend** — create `backend/.env`:

```env
GOOGLE_API_KEY=your-gemini-api-key
GEMINI_MODEL=gemini-2.5-flash
```

`GOOGLE_API_KEY` is read by `AIStudyGuideCalendar.py` via `python-dotenv`. Optional `GEMINI_MODEL` defaults to `gemini-2.5-flash`.

## How to run

Start both servers (two terminals):

```bash
# Terminal 1 — backend (from repo root, venv active)
cd backend
python app.py
# → http://127.0.0.1:5000
```

```bash
# Terminal 2 — frontend
cd frontend
npm run dev
# → http://localhost:5173 (Vite default)
```

Sign in with Google on the login page, add a course, upload PDFs, then open the calendar view to connect Google Calendar and sync reminders.

## Google Calendar setup

Calendar sync uses Firebase Google sign-in with the `calendar.events` scope. Configure this once per Firebase/Google Cloud project.

### 1. Enable APIs

In [Google Cloud Console](https://console.cloud.google.com/) (same project as Firebase):

1. **APIs & Services → Library**
2. Enable **Google Calendar API**
3. Ensure **Generative Language API** (Gemini) is enabled for the backend

### 2. OAuth consent screen

1. **APIs & Services → OAuth consent screen**
2. Choose **External** (or Internal for Workspace-only)
3. Add app name, support email, and developer contact
4. Under **Scopes**, add: `https://www.googleapis.com/auth/calendar.events`
5. Save

### 3. OAuth client (usually auto-managed by Firebase)

1. In **Firebase Console → Authentication → Sign-in method**, enable **Google**
2. Ensure authorized domains include `localhost` for local dev
3. If prompted, link or create an OAuth 2.0 Web client in Google Cloud

### 4. Test users (required in Testing mode)

While the OAuth app is in **Testing** publishing status:

1. **OAuth consent screen → Test users**
2. Add every Google account that will sign in locally or in staging
3. Non-test users will see `access_denied` until the app is published or they are added

### 5. In the app

1. Sign in with Google (login page requests calendar scope)
2. Open a course → **Calendar**
3. Click **Connect Google Calendar** if needed, then **Sync to Google Calendar**
4. Events appear on your primary calendar with reminders; sync metadata is saved in Firestore

## API overview

| Endpoint | Method | Purpose |
|----------|--------|---------|
| `/upload` | POST | Upload PDFs; run AI pipeline (guide, quiz, schedule, teach) |
| `/pushcourses` | POST | Save course list to Firestore |
| `/getsubjects` | POST | Fetch user courses and AI outputs |
| `/save-calendar-sync` | POST | Persist Google Calendar event IDs after sync |

All endpoints expect a Firebase ID token in the `Authorization` header.

## Known caveats & troubleshooting

| Issue | What to try |
|-------|-------------|
| **AI upload fails / quota errors** | Gemini free tier has rate limits; wait and retry. Check `GOOGLE_API_KEY` and backend logs. Uploads can take 30–60s due to intentional delays between Gemini calls. |
| **`access_denied` on Google sign-in** | Add your account under OAuth **Test users**, or publish the consent screen. |
| **Calendar sync fails / 401** | Re-click **Connect Google Calendar** — tokens live in `sessionStorage` and expire when the tab closes. |
| **Backend connection errors** | Confirm Flask is on port `5000` and CORS is allowed. Frontend calls `http://127.0.0.1:5000`. |
| **OCR poor quality** | Install Tesseract; use text-based PDFs when possible. |
| **Course not updating after upload** | Course name on upload must match an existing subject in Firestore. |
| **Missing Firebase config** | Ensure all `VITE_FIREBASE_*` vars are set; restart `npm run dev` after changing `.env`. |

